[SourceTitle "01 Introduction"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "gm-avrukh-against-the-scotch-game/course/5884, variation/230039"]

{After the move sequence...} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {The move characteristic of the 
Scotch game is:} 3. d4 {While dating back from the 18th century, the Scotch game only 
got its name following a correspondance match between Edinburgh and London. The 
Scotch remained less popular than the Spanish or Italian game, until it was 
succesfully revived by none other than Garry Kasparov during the 1990 World 
Championship match against Anatoly Karpov. Nowadays, the Scotch game is played 
regularly by numerous super GMs including amongst others Magnus Carlsen, Anish Giri 
and Maxime Vachier-Lagrave. After the further} exd4 4. Nxd4 {we will base our 
repertoire on the active move} Bc5 {From this position, we will cover all important 
White alternatives, namely: 5. Nb3 will be our main line.} ({5. Be3 the approach 
chosen by Kasparov in his return to chess last year.}) ({5. Nxc6 is another key line, 
and was the choice of John Shaw in his recent 1 e4 repertoire book.}) ({5. Nf5?! is 
the first move we will study. It is objectively not good but Black needs to know what 
he is doing.}) ({5. c3 will transpose to a line we cover under 5. Be3}) 5. Nb3 *

