[SourceTitle "02 The tricky 5. Nf5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "gm-avrukh-against-the-scotch-game/course/5884, variation/230040"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nf5 $6 {A very aggressive approach, 
which requires good theoretical knowledge from Black.} d5 $1 {Only like this!} ({One 
of the ideas behind 5. Nf5 is that after the natural 5... g6?! 6. Be3 Bxe3 7. Nxe3 
followed by c4 and Nc3 White has all the chances to fight for advantage.}) 6. Nxg7+ 
({White already needs to be careful. For instance after 6. exd5?! Bxf5 7. Qe2+} ({7. 
dxc6? loses to Bxf2+}) {Black has 7... Nge7!⩲ A natural improvement over} ({7... 
Nce7 8. Qb5+ c6 9. Qxc5 with unclear platy in Schmidt,K-Feige,M Torgelow 1994}) {8. 
dxc6 bxc6!!6 and Black development advantage should give him an excellent game.}) Kf8 
7. Nh5 ({7. Nf5? is already practically losing after Bxf5 8. exf5 Qh4! 9. Qf3} ({9. 
g3 runs into Qe4+ followed by 10... Qh1}) {9... Re8+ 10. Kd1 Nf6??0 with a crushing 
attack Castro Rojas,O (2415) -Garcia,G (2400) Bogota 1986}) Qh4 8. Ng3 Nf6 {Of course 
not} ({8... dxe4?! 9. Qd5 and the e4-pawn is falling.}) 9. Be2 ({9. exd5?! is hardly 
acceptable for White. After Ng4! 10. dxc6 Bxf2+ 11. Kd2 occured in Jaszczowski,Z 
(992) -Henock,R (512) LSS email 2010} ({11. Ke2 Qe7+ 12. Kf3 Bb6−+ is hopeless for 
White, as Black as the extremely strong threats of Ne5.}) {Now 11... Nxh2!⩲ is very 
strong, for example 12. Bd3 Qxg3} ({12... Bg4!? is actually even better}) {13. Qe2 
bxc6!? with clearly dangerous position for Black.}) dxe4 10. O-O {Another option} 
({10. Nc3 Be6 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Rd8 13. Qc1 was played in the model game 
Yakovich-Goldin, Moscow 1994. Here I found the improvement Ne5⩲ 14. b3} ({14. O-O 
Neg4??0 leads to Black's strong attack.}) {14... Rg8 15. Qa3+ Ke8 16. Ncxe4 Nxe4 17. 
Qa4+ Nc6 18. Qxe4 Qxe4 19. Nxe4 Rxg2⩱ and Black is obviously better in this endgame 
due to his better pawn structure.}) h5 $1 {A very spectacular and important move in 
Black's strategy; the threat of 11... Ng4 forces White to play} 11. Be3 Bd6 $1 {This 
is very powerful move, which I have discovered recently. It creates the immediate 
threat 12... Ng4 13 h3 Ne3 winning.} ({11... Bxe3 12. fxe3 Qg5 is just a normal line, 
which has been played a few times; Black is doing absolutely fine but White is not 
worse either.}) ({11... Bb6!?⩲ deserves some attention.}) 12. Bd4 {Another line 
here} ({12. Qd2 seems natural but runs into Ng4! 13. h3 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Bxh3 and it 
seems like White resigned early in Roewekamp, K-Malmstroem,J DESC email 2003. 
Neverthless Black is clearly better after 15. Qxe4} ({15. gxh3 Rg8−+ with a 
decisive attack.}) {15... Bf4! with strong attacking position for Black.}) Nxd4 13. 
Qxd4 {Here we have been following the game Zagema,W (2355) -Liss,E (2480) Groningen 
1994. Black could have played the very strong} Rh6 $146 {and play could continue} 
({13... Rh7 is also interesting}) 14. Nc3 b6 15. Rad1 ({15. Ncxe4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 
Bxg3!−+ and Black wins.}) Bb7 $17 {and Black has very promising attacking 
position.} *

