[Comment "gm-avrukh-against-the-scotch-game/course/5884, variation/230042"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bd3 Qh4 $1 {This 
idea/concept is the main reason why this line has been appealing to me. Black 
immediately takes the initiative on the kingside.} 7. Qe2 ({7. O-O Nf6 Enables Black 
to create interesting ideas on the kingside 8. Qf3 Other options} ({8. h3? looks 
natural, but allows Black to seize a very dangerous initiative on the kingisde d5! 9. 
exd5 Bxh3! 10. Qe2+} ({10. gxh3 Obviously loses to Qg3+ 11. Kh1 Qxh3+ 12. Kg1 Bd6 
there is one game here, which went 13. Qe2+ Kd8 14. f4 Bc5+ 15. Rf2 Ng4 and Black won 
easily Bayasgalan, K-Talalov,A (1707) Maribor 2012}) {10... Kf8 11. Be3 Bd6 12. gxh3 
Qxh3 13. f3 Yu,S (2290) -Castiglione,M (2225) Guarapuava 1995 and now simply Nxd5!⩲ 
threatening Re8 14. Bd4 Nf4 15. Qf2 Qh5−+ would have decided the game easily.}) 
({8. Qd2 O-O 9. Qf4 with the very reasonable idea to get rid of Black queen therefore 
securing the position of White king Qxf4 10. Bxf4 d6 The arising endgame is very 
reliable for Black 11. Nd2?! Hardly a good square for White knight} ({11. Nc3 Bd4 
would have led to balanced play}) {11... Nh5! 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Nf4 14. Nb3 Nxd3 15. 
cxd3 Bb6⩱ and Black was already better due to his bishop's pair in 
Alatortsev,V-Lilienthal,A Leningrad 1935}) {8... O-O 9. Bf4} ({A very interesting 
tactical battle occured in the following game 9. e5 Ng4 10. Bf4 Bd4! 11. Bg3 Nxe5 12. 
Qf5 d6 13. Bxh4} ({13. Qxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxh4 Bxb2 15. Nd2 Bxa1 16. Rxa1 improves 
slightly over the main game, and is a complex but about equal endgame.}) {13... Bxf5 
14. Bxf5 Bxb2 15. Nd2 Bxa1 16. Rxa1 Rab8 and Black emerged with good position from 
complications in Huschenbeth,N (2542) -L'Ami,E (2626) Vlissingen 2013}) {9... d6 10. 
e5} ({After the natural 10. h3 Nh5 11. Bh2 Black has the beautiful and unexpected g5! 
Black's threat is 12... g4 12. e5} ({12. Be2 looks meek but might be the best 
defense. Black can play either 12... Nf4 or 12... g4, with no problems in either 
case.}) {12... d5 13. Bf5} ({13. g4? runs into the powerful f6 , intending to open 
the f-file with a strong attack. For instance after 14. gxh5 fxe5 15. Qg3 Qxh5 the 
attack rages on, Black having ideas such as... Bh3, ... Bd6 or. ..e4.}) {13... Bxf5 
14. Qxf5 this happened in Nakhapetiane,P (2495) -Efimenko, Z (2708) Olginka 2011. In 
this position I found a strong improvement in the form of Ng7⩲ 15. Qf6 worse} ({15. 
Qf3?! Rab8 16. b3 f5 17. exf6 Nh5??0 and once again Black initiative is very 
dangeorus.}) {15... Rae8 16. Qxc6 Qc4! The main point, not only defending the bishop, 
but also threatening Bxf2. 17. Qh6 Ne6 18. Nd2 Qxc2 19. Nf3 Qg6 20. Qxg6+ fxg6⩱ and 
Black is slightly better, thanks to White poor h2-bishop.}) {10... Nd5 11. Bg3 Qg4 
12. Qxg4 Bxg4 13. exd6 cxd6 with a roughly equal game Cuccumini,V-Risovic,A ICCF 
email 2011. Black will proceed with... Rfb8 and play on the queenside.}) Nf6 8. h3 
({The safe approach for White considered to be 8. Be3 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 O-O 10. Nd2 and is 
in fact the line chose by Shaw, and has been played by Carlsen. 10 Nd2 is a good 
multi-purpose move, intending Nf3 and short castling.} ({In the sharper line 10. Nc3 
Re8 11. O-O-O the following game is very important d6 12. f4 Nd5! 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. 
e5 Rublevsky,S (2693) -Bruzon Batista,L (2713) Poikovsky 2012 and now dxe5⩲ 15. 
fxe5 Qe7 16. Bb5 Bd7 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. Qd4 c6 19. Rhf1 Re6⩱ would even led to 
slight pull for Black due to White weak e5-pawn.}) {10... Re8 11. O-O} ({11. Nf3 
might be less precise as after Qh5 12. O-O Black has d5}) {11... d6 12. Rfe1} 
({Another model and one of my favourites games in this line went 12. Rae1 a5 13. Qg3} 
({13. Nf3 is an improvement given by Shaw. Qh5 14. Qf4 'intending e4-e5, offers White 
chances of a small edge' (Shaw) . but now Bg4 is a simple way to parry the e5 plan by 
White. 15. Nd4 Bd7 is equal.}) {13... Qxg3 14. hxg3 a4! 15. f3 Be6 16. b3 Nd7 17. Re3 
axb3} ({17... Ne5!? was fine as well}) {18. axb3 Ne5 19. Be2 Ra2 20. Rc3 c5⩱ and 
Black was pressing the rest of the game in Carlsen, M (2714) -Kamsky,G (2714) 
Khanty-Mansiysk 2007}) {12... Ng4 13. Qg3 Qxg3 14. hxg3 Rb8 15. b3 Be6 gave Black a 
reliable endgame in Bacallao Alonso,Y (2526) -Quesada Vera,L (2415) Santa Clara 2014} 
({15... Ne5 16. Be2 is also mentioned in Shaw's 1 e4 repertoire. At this stage the 
endgame looks about equal.})) d5 $3 {Probably the most important finesse in this 
line, and the move which has given this variation a second life} 9. g3 ({Obviously a 
very important line here is 9. exd5+ Kd8! threatening 10... Re8 10. O-O The start of 
sequence of forced moves Bxh3! Of course 11. Qe5} ({JS: 11. dxc6 looks suicidal but 
Black has to play good moves to keep an edge Bd6!} ({after 11... Bg4 12. Qe5 Bd6 
White survives with 13. Bg5 Bxe5 14. Bxh4 Bxb2 15. Nd2 Bxa1 16. Rxa1 and this endgame 
is unclear.}) {12. g3 Bxg3 13. fxg3 Qxg3+ 14. Kh1 Bxf1 15. Qxf1 Re8 16. Bd2 Ng4 and 
Black is better}) {11... Bxg2} ({11... Bxf2+ 12. Rxf2 Qxf2+ 13. Kxf2 Ng4+ 14. Kg3 
Nxe5 15. gxh3 Nxd3 16. cxd3 cxd5 17. Nc3 Rb8∞ leads to unclear play but I would 
rather play White with the two minor pieces.}) {12. Kxg2 Bd6 13. Qf5 Qh2+ 14. Kf3 
Re8! Bringing fuel to the attack, and threatening... Re5 15. Bg5} ({15. Bf4? is bad 
on view of Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qh5+ 17. Kg2 Re5!−+ intending... Rg5 with a with winning 
attack.}) {15... Qh5+ 16. Kg2 Qh2+= and it was perpetual in Nataf-Istratescu, FRA-ch 
2014}) Qh5 10. Qxh5 Nxh5 11. Nc3 ({A key point here is that 11. e5? is bad in view of 
Bd4 12. g4 Nf4! 13. Bxf4 Bxb2 14. Kd2 Bxa1 and Black was winning in Nataf,I (2534) 
-Fressinet,L (2673) Pau 2008}) O-O 12. g4 Nf6 {and now we have two lines:} 13. Be3 
{and} Bb6 ({13. exd5 Re8+ 14. Be3} ({even worse is 14. Kf1?! cxd5 15. g5 Ne4!!6}) 
{Petrosian,D (2501) -Melkumyan,H (2583) Yerevan 2010 and now Black should have played 
14... cxd5!⩲ 15. O-O Bxe3 16. fxe3 Re5⩱ with a pleasant endgame.}) 14. exd5 
{Petrosian,D (2480) -Petrosyan,T (2236) Jermuk 2011. Black has now a simple 
improvement in} cxd5 $146 15. Bxb6 axb6 {which leads to a comfortable endgame for 
Black. I believe Black was concerned about} 16. g5 $6 {but is fails tactically to} 
({better is 16. O-O= with equal play.}) Nh5 17. Nxd5 Bb7 18. c4 Nf4 $36 {and Black is 
better.} *

