1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Nc3 ({6. Bc4 Qh4 7. Qe2 
Nf6 and we agree with Shaw who mentions that the Bishop is not well placed on c4, 
given Black's intented O-O, Re8 and d5.}) d6 7. Bd3 {I had a game after} ({7. Na4 
Bb6! 8. Nxb6 axb6 Black has a very compact pawn structure to compensate the loss of 
the Bishop's pair. 9. Bd3 Ne7 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bd2 O-O 12. Qe2 Jones,G (2575) -Avrukh,B 
(2625) London 2010 Now I should have played Ng6⩲ 13. O-O Re8= with idea 14... d5}) 
Ne7 {The best square for the knight, as after} ({7... Nf6?! 8. Na4 Bb6 9. O-O⩲ the 
idea of Bg5 is annoying.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Kh1 {In case of} ({9. Na4 we have Bb6 as 
usual}) Bb6 10. f4 f5 {Obviously Black cannot allow f4-f5.} 11. Bd2 d5 ({Worth 
considering is 11... fxe4!?⩲ 12. Nxe4 Nf5∞ with a complicated game.}) 12. exd5 
({JS: 12. e5 gives an edge according to the machine. While the position remains 
complex and interesting, those who prefer it can play the suggested improvement on 
move 11.}) cxd5 13. Qf3 Bb7 14. Rae1 Qd7 {with very interesting and complex 
middlegame. Black has ideas of occupying the center with c5.} *

