[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "gm-avrukh-against-the-scotch-game/course/5884, variation/230044"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 {This continuation will be our main 
move.} Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2 {The main move, which has become popular thanks to 
Magnus' games. White has other options as well:} O-O ({I have to mention the 
remarkable 7... a5!? 8. e5 O-O which has first been played first in Vachier Lagrave,M 
(2768) -Carlsen,M (2877) Saint Louis 2014. Black scores very-well here, but it looks 
too crazy for me.}) 8. Be3 ({The alternative is 8. Bg5 Here I would recommend h6} 
({For some time I prefered 8... Nd4 but have changed my mind after the following game 
9. Qd2 Nxb3 10. axb3 Re8 11. O-O-O h6 12. h4!? Cheparinov,I (2681) -Melkumyan,H 
(2613) Yerevan 2014}) {9. Bh4 a5! A very important resource. White has two options 
now: 10. O-O-O and} ({10. a4 Nd4 11. Qd3 Nxb3 12. cxb3 Black had been struggling in 
this position until the discovery of c6! 13. O-O-O d5 and now 14. Qc2} ({Obvioulsy 
the critical sequence of moves 14. exd5 cxd5 15. Nxd5} ({15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nxd5 
Qxf2⩱ is just fine for Black.}) {15... g5! Amazingly enough White should be very 
careful here and probably the best idea for him to force draw by means of 16. Qf3} 
({16. Bg3 runs into Be6! 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. Qb5 Qxb5 19. Bxb5 Bxb3⩱ with ideas of... 
Ne4. Black is better.}) {16... Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Qc7+ 18. Bc4 Be6} ({18... gxh4 also 
leads to the same result 19. Qf6 Be6 20. Rg5+ hxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qh5+=}) {19. 
Bxg5 Bxd5 20. Qxd5 hxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 Nataf,I 
(2531) -Fressinet,L (2692) Drancy 2016}) ({14. e5 g5 and Black is better.}) {14... 
Qd6 15. Kb1 so far following Negi,P (2638) -Karpatchev,A (2484) Baden-Baden 2013. I 
found a really nice improvement for Black: d4!⩲ 16. Bc4 Re8 17. f3 Nd7⩱ with 
better game for Black.}) {10... a4 11. Nd2 a3 12. e5 axb2+ 13. Kb1 Bd4!⩲ A very 
important novelty, which basically repairs this line, which has been always 
considered bad for Black due to the following game} ({13... Nd5? 14. Nxd5! Qxh4 15. 
Ne4 d6 16. Ndf6+ gxf6 17. g3 which wins the Queen, with a decisive advantage Vallejo 
Pons,F (2695) -Tkachiev,V (2632) Legnica 2013}) {14. exf6} ({14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qg4+ 
Kh8 16. Qh3 Kg7= leads to a repetition.}) {14... Bxc3 15. Ne4} ({Another remarkable 
line here goes 15. fxg7 Qxh4 16. Qe4 Qf6 17. Qh7+!! Kxh7 18. gxf8=Q Nb4 Suddenly 
Black has deadly threats 19. Bd3+ Nxd3 20. Ne4 Qg7 21. Qxg7+ Bxg7 22. Rxd3 d6??4 and 
Black has full compensation for the exchange thanks to his powerful bishop's pair.}) 
{15... Bd4 16. Qh5 Ra5! 17. Bb5 Re8 18. fxg7 Rxb5 19. Bxd8 Rxh5 20. Rxd4 Rf5 21. Nf6+ 
Rxf6 22. Bxf6 Nxd4 23. Bxd4 Re6= followed by 24... f6 and 25... Kf7 with an equal 
endgame.}) d5 $1 {It took me some time to realize, but this move is essential. 
Without this break Black has a very passive position.} 9. O-O-O d4 $1 {And this is 
the key follow-up. The pin along d-file look annoying, but Black has everything in 
order..} 10. Bg5 {The most interesting move for White} ({10. Na4?! seems logical, 
threatening the Bishop supporting the d4 pawn, but is dubious due to Qe8! a move with 
beautiful geometry! Black unpins the d4 pawn so the Be3 is now en prise. At the same 
time, the Black Queen eyes the Na4 through the Nc6, so as to force White to capture 
on b6 before taking on d4. This in turn allows Black to recapture on b6 with the 
a-pawn, after which... Ra2 becomes possible. 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Bxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 
Fercec,N (2471) -Zelic,M (2307) Zadar 2013 and now c5! 14. Rd1 Rxa2 15. Kb1 Qa4−+ 
would have led to decisive attack.}) ({10. f3 Be6 11. Bg5 Darini, P (2479) 
-Khomeriki,N (2228) Nakhchivan 2015} ({Clearly worse is 11. Bf2?! as it runs into 
tactics Ng4! 12. fxg4 Qg5+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Rxd2 dxc3 15. bxc3 Bxf2 16. Rxf2 Bxg4 
and Black positional's advantage is beyond any doubts Nezar,M (2396) -Szabo,K (2545) 
Haguenau 2013}) {Now I like the following improvement 11... h6⩲6 12. Bh4 Nb4 13. 
Qe1 a5! and it seems to me Black has a very good chances to create a dangerous 
initiative on the queenside.}) ({10. Nb5?! hardly a good idea. Nxe4! Objectively the 
best, although it was hard to refrain from} ({10... dxe3!? 11. Rxd8 Rxd8 12. f3 
Be6??4 which brought me a nice win Li, R (2426) - Avrukh,B (2609) Chicago 2015. The 
arising position objectively is not so clear though.}) {11. N3xd4} ({11. N5xd4 In the 
game Grzesik,G (1734) -Neumann,F (1812) Prague 2016 Black missed Nb4 threatening... 
Na2 followed by a reloader fork on c3. 12. Kb1 Nd5⩱ with clearly better chances.}) 
{11... Nb4!∞ 12. Ne6? Nxa2+ 13. Kb1 Bxe6 14. Rxd8 Rfxd8 and Black is almost winning 
Sinyanskiy,M (2042) -Ambartsumova,K (2307) Kazan 2016}) h6 11. Bh4 Re8 12. Nd5 {Looks 
critical.} ({Another important games went 12. f3 Be6 13. Kb1 Anand,V (2783) 
-Fressinet,L (2706) Paris/St Petersburg 2013 Black should have played Ne5!⩲ 14. 
Na4} ({14. Qe1 Ng6 15. Bf2 c5⩱ is very good for Black.}) {14... Bxb3 15. axb3 d3 
16. cxd3 Bd4??4 following up by an attack on the queenside by means of a5, b5, a4 
etc.}) g5 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Bg3 a5 $1 {Given his weakened kingside, Black has to 
react very fast. This move plans... a4 and... a3.} 15. a3 {Both} ({15. Kb1 a4 16. Nc1 
a3??0}) ({15. a4 Nb4 leaves Black much better.}) ({JS: the computer suggests 15. Nd2 
Nb4∞}) a4 16. Nd2 d3 $1 17. Qxd3 ({17. cxd3 leaves White crushed positionally. 
After Bd4 18. Nf3 Ra6??0 Black has a strong queenside attack in addition to the 
domination of the d4 square.}) Bg4 18. Be2 $5 ({18. f3 improves. Nevertheless after 
Red8 19. Qe2 Be6??4 Black has fantastic compensation, in the form of superior 
development, play on the queenside and on White's weak dark squares.}) Red8 19. e5 
({19. Qc4? doesn't save the day on account of Be6 20. Qc3 Bd4∓}) {So far we have 
followed Fercec,N (2471) -Brkic,A (2566) Zadar 2013. Now Black has a clear 
improvement with} Qg7 $146 {which leaves White with the Queen en prise and with a 
weak e5 pawn.} 20. Qe4 Rd4 21. Bxg4 Rxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe5 $17 {and White does not have 
enough for the queen.} *

