[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "gm-avrukh-against-the-scotch-game/course/5884, variation/230045"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bg5 {this move 
has been played by Carlsen and Giri and is thus a serious continuation.} ({7. Qf3 is 
another move which has been played by very strong GM's. There is only a single game 
with Nd4!? but I like this move. The game saw 8. Nxd4 Bxd4 9. Ne2 Be5 10. Qd3?! c6! 
11. f4 Bc7 12. Ng3 O-O 13. Bd2 d5! 14. e5 Nd7 15. Qe2 Nc5 16. b4 Ne6∓ and Black was 
clearly better in Li,R (2486) -Raznikov,D (2506) Dallas 2016}) h6 {Always useful to 
insert this move.} 8. Bh4 Qe7 $1 ({This is the right move order for Black, as 8... d6 
gives White the option to go for a different set-up with 9. f3 Be6 10. Bb5 After 8... 
Qe7, we now examine two lines:}) 9. Qe2 {and} g5 ({9. Bd3 was recently played by 
Giri, but Black equalised convincingly in the following game g5! 10. Bg3 d5 11. Qe2 
dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bd7 14. O-O-O O-O-O= Giri,A (2782) -Fressinet,L (2687) 
Paris 2016}) 10. Bg3 d6 11. h4 Rg8 $1 {keeping the g5-pawn in place and good control 
over the dark squares.} 12. O-O-O Be6 13. hxg5 hxg5 14. Rh6 O-O-O {Black is very 
comfortable} 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Ne5 17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Qf3 Ne8 $1 {The black knight 
is heading for d6, giving Black a comfortable game as in Gopal-Avrukh, Chicago 2014} 
({There is also nothing wrong with 18... Rd6 19. Nd2 Ne8 20. Rh5 Rublevsky-Grischuk, 
Candidates 2007 and now Kb8! with a nice game for Black.}) *

