1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 {And now it is important to be 
prepared for the tricky Nb5 since play can become complicated rather quickly.} 6. Nb5 
Bxe3 7. fxe3 Qh4+ $1 8. g3 Qd8 9. Qg4 g6 10. Qf4 d6 11. N1c3 {A key intermezzo, 
forcing White to weaken the light-squares with} a6 12. Nd4 Ne5 13. Be2 Bh3 14. O-O-O 
Nf6 15. Qh6 ({8... Qxe4 is more complex and rather theoretical, the main line going 
9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Nf6∞}) Bg4 {A logical follow-up. In case of} ({9. N1c3 a6 10. 
Nd4 Nf6 11. Nxc6 dxc6⩱ Black is obvioulsy better.}) 16. h3 Bxe2 ({also interesting 
is the more aggressive 9... g5!?}) 17. Ndxe2 Qe7 ({A logical follow-up to White's 
aggressive strategy would be 11. Bc4 and it is in fact the most commonly played move 
in the position. This said, it does not work well since after Ne5 12. O-O Black is 
able to refute White's play with the folloiwing remarkable line: Bh3! 13. Bxf7+ Kd7! 
14. N1c3} ({Even worse is 14. Rd1? Qe7! threatening... Rf8 15. Bxg8 g5! 16. Qf2 Rf8 
17. Qe2 Bg4 0-1 Morais Carreras-Castillo Martinez,E Llinars del Valles 2014}) {14... 
g5 15. Qxe5} ({After 15. Qf2 Nh6 16. Bb3 Rf8 White is busted positionally. The 
endgame after 17. Qxf8 Qxf8 18. Rxf8 Rxf8−+ is absolutely lost, as has been proven 
in 2 games. Black has ideas of... Nhg4 followed by.. . Rf2.}) {15... dxe5 16. Rad1+} 
({16. Rfd1+ doesn't change much Ke7 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxg8 Rhxg8 19. Nd5+ Kf7 20. 
Nbxc7 Rgf8 21. Nb5 Kg7 and Black is just winning 0-1 (35) Duboue,P (2292) -Terrieux,K 
(2409) Sautron 2014}) {16... Ke7 17. Nd5+ Kf8 18. Nbxc7 this occured in Wang,H (2512) 
-Harikrishna,P (2645) Tiayuan 2005} ({18. Be6+ doesn't work after Bxf1 19. Rxf1+ Kg7 
20. Rf7+ Kg6−+}) {Now the cool 18... Nh6!−+ would have finished the job. White is 
lost.}) 18. Rhf1 O-O-O $15 ({14... h5!? also looks pretty good for Black Ronchetti,N 
(2423) -Brunello,S (2476) Arvier 2010}) {now Black slowly consolidates his position 
and should enjoy positional a edge, as in the following two games. Black is already 
better thanks to White's poor pawn structure, Asadli,V (2287) -Adhiban, B (2646) 
Nakhchivan 2015 and now I prefer the safe approach with} *

