1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. g3 d5 $1 {A 
well-timed center break very thematic for this line} 8. Bg2 dxe4 {Now White has some 
choice:} 9. Nd2 {The main continuation} ({9. Bxe4 Black easily achieves a comfortable 
play by means of Bxd4 10. cxd4 Bf5 11. Bg2 Rd8⩱ Kiolbasa,O (1761) -Harazinska,E 
(1947) Suchedniow 2012}) ({9. Nb5 is quite tricky. Bxe3 10. Nxc7+ Kf8 11. fxe3} ({11. 
O-O In case of Rb8 12. fxe3 Qe5! 13. Qb3 f5 14. Nb5 Be6 15. Qa4 g6 16. Nd4 Kg7 and 
Black maintains is better positionally, due to White's passive light-squared bishop, 
as well as ideas to play ...h5-h4, Szurovszky,E (2097) -Bernath,R (2141) Hungary 
2009}) {11... Rb8 12. Nd5} ({White is objectively worse after 12. Na3 as, to my great 
surprise, I realized that h5! is extremely strong here. The key game went 13. Rf1} 
({It is too dangerous for White to take Black's central pawn with 13. Bxe4 as after 
Qe5 14. Bxc6 Nxc6 15. Ncb5 Rh6∓ Black has a large plus.}) {13... Qe5 14. Ncb5 Bg4 
15. Qd2 Rd8 16. Nd4 Zhang,P (2623) -Hracek,Z (2593) Turin 2006 and now simply 
Nxd4⩲6 17. exd4 Qe6⩱ would maintain a nice edge for Black.}) {12... Qe5 13. Nxe7 
Kxe7 14. Nd2 was played in two games. Here I like the novelty h5!?⩲ 15. Nxe4} ({15. 
O-O f5⩱ once again gives Blacka nice edge, as he shuts down White light-squared 
bishop.}) {15... f5 16. Ng5 Qxe3+ 17. Qe2 Qxe2+ 18. Kxe2 h4= and Black has a very 
comfortable endgame.}) Bb6 10. Nxe4 ({10. O-O O-O 11. Nxe4 Qg6 is just a 
transposition to 10. Ne4}) Qg6 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 {In my opinion the main move.} 
({12. Nc5 Another important line is Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc6 14. Re1 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 c6 16. a4 
a5 and Black had equalized in Smeets,J (2532) -Kramnik,V (2766) Netherlands 2007}) 
Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc6 14. Bxb6 axb6 15. Qd2 {preparing Qf4.} f6 $5 16. Qf4 {this has been 
occured in Navara,D (2616) -Haba,P (2531) Czechia 2005, where White won a crushing 
game after 16... Ne5 17. Ng5!. Meanwhile the accurate} Qf7 $1 {intending ... Ne5 and 
... Be6, would consolidate Black position with equal play.} *

