[SourceTitle "10 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bc4"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "gm-avrukh-against-the-scotch-game/course/5884, variation/230049"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bc4 {this is the 
big main line.} O-O 8. O-O {Black has a wide choice here, but I settled on} b6 {This 
move is played less often than the alternatives, but scores very well for Black. 8... 
b6 is a good multi-purpose move, which protects the c5-bishop and allows the light 
square bishop to develop on b7 or even on a6, as we will see in some of the lines 
that follow. Now I checked four possibilities for White:} 9. Nc2 {Main move} ({9. Qd2 
Qg6 10. Nxc6} ({Dubious is 10. f3?! d5! 11. Bxd5} ({11. exd5?! Ne5 12. Bb3 Ba6 Black 
has a very dangerous initiative Roubaud,A (2172) -Rouffignac,T (2046) Saint Paul 
Trois Chateaux 2013}) {11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Ne5 13. b4?! Nc4 14. Qf2 Bd6 15. Nd2 Qh5 
16. h3 Moradiabadi,E (2547) -Georgiev,V (2537) Ravana 2009 and now the simple Qxd5⩱ 
would secure Black an advantage.}) {10... Qxc6 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Na3 a5! 13. Rfe1} 
({13. Qd4 Queen's trade should have led to easy equality for Black Qxd4 14. cxd4 d5! 
15. exd5 Bartel,M (2623) -Sargissian,G (2679) Baku 2015. Now the simple Bb7⩲6 16. 
d6 cxd6 17. Nb5 Ba6! would equalise easily.}) {13... d6 14. Bf1 this position occured 
in Bacallao Alonso, Y (2554) -Quesada Perez,Y (2631) Varadero 2016. I believe Black 
should have played Bd7⩲6 15. Nc2 Rfe8 16. Nd4 b5 with a very reliable position.}) 
({9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. Bxc5 Qxc5 11. Qd4 d6 12. Qxc5 In case of} ({12. Nd2 Be6 Black is 
fine as well.}) {12... bxc5 13. Nd2 a5 Black has good counterplay on the queenside 
14. b3 Ba6 15. Rab1 Rfb8 with a balanced position Nabaty,T (2485) -Howell,D (2612) 
Rijeka 2010}) ({9. f4 d5! An important break to remember! Without this move, Black 
would be worse. 10. exd5} ({A key tactical point is that 10. e5? is refuted by Qh6 
11. Be2 Nxe5!∓ with a clear advantage to Black, Kosteniuk,A (2524) -Zhukova,N 
(2492) Dagomys 2010}) {10... Na5 11. Bd3 Bb7! Another key move to remember. 
Everything works tactically for Black. The key model game here} ({11... Nxd5? 12. Qh5 
is not what we are looking for!}) {12. Nd2} ({It's important that 12. b4? doesn't 
work on account of the nice sequence Nxd5 13. Bf2 Nxb4!} ({JS: the machine gives 
13... Nxf4 as being even stronger.}) {14. cxb4 Bxd4 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Bxd4 Qg6 and 
Black seizes the initiative. The immediate threat is... Qg2 mate, and Black will 
follow-up with Rad8.}) {12... Nxd5 13. Ne4 Qe7 14. Bd2} ({JS: on 14. Bf2 Black has 
Bxd4 15. Bxd4 Nc6 with a good game, as White has no satisfying way to avoid the 
exchange of the d4 bishop.}) {14... Nc4!? It seems like Black has other options as 
well} ({14... Nf6!? and}) ({14... Nc6!?}) {15. Ng5 Nxd2 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Be4} ({JS: 
it is worth mentioning that 17. Qh5 does not work on account of Nf6 18. Qh4 g6!}) 
{17... Nf6 18. Bxb7 Nxf1 19. Bxa8 Ne3 20. Qf3 Nc2 21. Rd1 Rd8 22. Kh1 Nxd4 23. cxd4 
Rxd4= and after wild complications the position has settled for drawish equality, 
Engelhard,C (1851) -Kraft,D (1997) GER email 2008.}) Ne5 10. Be2 Bb7 $5 {The 
following game has inspired me to examine this move.} ({Also sound is 10... N5g6 11. 
Nd2} ({11. Bxc5 bxc5 leads to a double-edged pawn structure. Black will follow-up 
with... d6 and... Rb8.}) {11... Bxe3 12. Nxe3 Bb7 13. Re1 d5 and Black delivered a 
thematic break, equalising easily Najer,E (2681) -Pashikian,A (2663) Ohrid 2009.}) 
11. f4 N5g6 12. e5 Qe6 $6 13. b4 {Probably this is the place where White should think 
about possible improvements, but Black seems OK in any case.} Bxe3+ 14. Nxe3 Nh4 $1 
15. Bg4 f5 $1 16. Be2 Kh8 17. Bc4 Qg6 18. Rf2 d6 19. exd6 Rad8 $36 {and Black took 
over in Kasparov,G (2812) -Caruana,F (2795) Saint Louis 2016.} *

