1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. O-O b6 
{This move is played less often than the alternatives, but scores very well for 
Black. 8... b6 is a good multi-purpose move, which protects the c5-bishop and allows 
the light square bishop to develop on b7 or even on a6, as we will see in some of the 
lines that follow. Now I checked four possibilities for White:} 9. f4 d5 $1 {An 
important break to remember! Without this move, Black would be worse.} 10. exd5 Na5 
11. Bd3 Bb7 $1 {Another key move to remember. Everything works tactically for Black. 
It's important that} 12. b4 $2 {doesn't work on account of the nice sequence} Nxd5 
13. Bf2 Nxb4 $1 14. cxb4 Bxd4 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Bxd4 Qg6 {and Black seizes the 
initiative. The immediate threat is... Qg2 mate, and Black will follow-up with Rad8.} 
*

